GDP per Capita and Life Expectancy at Birth Examined Over Time¶

I. Introduction¶

A rich person lives longer than a poor person, holding other factors constant. They can afford better healthcare, afford to shop at Whole Foods (or send someone there), get blood transfusions from young people (https://www.ivyplasma.com/), et cetera. It stands to reason that as countries get wealthier that they should be able to afford better healthcare systems, if not the latter two, and that life expectancy should rise. It also stands to reason that people living longer, work longer and that being healthier means fewer people as a proportion drop out of the labor force due to illness.

My hypothesis is that returns to life expectancy at birth from increases in GDP per Capita are diminishing as the world becomes richer on aggregate. This is because there should be a natural limit on the length of a human life and that approaching it is more difficult and difficult the closer you get. Also, it is easy to conceive of countries consuming more unhealthy luxury items as they get richer. Therefore, I expect the coefficients in my repeated OLS models to be positive, but decreasing over time.

I'm sure there is plenty of literature on this question, but I chose not to research it because I did not want to bias the way I approached this problem and just end up recreating someone else's work. Also, engaging writing techniques don't seem to be taught in economics departments and I wanted to spare myself the drudgery.

*Life expectancy is at birth is measured in years and GDP per capita is in current US dollars (as of 7/10/2019).

II. Data Cleaning and Sample Selection¶

TL;DR: I used World Bank data for each variable during the period from 1990 to 2017 for reasons of data availability.

I got the life expectancy at birth data from https://data.worldbank.org/indicator/sp.dyn.le00.in and the GDP per Capita data from https://data.worldbank.org/indicator/ny.gdp.pcap.cd.

# defines a function to drop years from a dataframe
def year_dropper(df, start_year, end_year):
    # creates and empty list of years for dropping
    year_drop = []
    # for year in the range of years we want to drop
    for year in range(start_year, end_year + 1):
        # converts it to a string for column referencing and appends it to the list 
        year_drop.append(str(year))
    # for year the list of years to drop
    for year in year_drop:
        # drops the years needed to be dropped from the dataframe
        df = df.drop(year, axis = 1)
    
    # returns the dataframe
    return(df)

# defines a function to display the histograms of input variables
def disp_histograms(df, cols, variable, start_year):
    # this block of code displays the distribution of the amount of growth in years in each
    # period

    # initializes the year at start_year, which is the first year in our dataset
    year = start_year
    # loops through the delta life expectancy at birth columns
    for i in cols:
        # creates a title for the plot
        title = 'Distribution of ' + variable + ' in Year: ' + str(year)
        # plots the column
        plt.hist(df[i])
        # adds the title
        plt.title(title)
        # displays the plot
        plt.show()
        # increments the count to move on to the next column
        year += 1

Life expectancy at birth skews left, which is good because that means the mass of the distribution is on the side of living longer. The x-axis also creeps right over time showing the growth in life expectancy for the world.

IV. Modeling¶

Here I define some functions to make repeated model estimation and graphing easier.

In [54]:
# creates a function capable of repeated difference in difference modeling provided the
# inputed dataframe contains both the y and X variables, and takes in the dataframe, and 
# ordered lists of y and X columns
def repeated_reg(df, y_cols, X_cols):

    # imports the statsmodels library
    import statsmodels.api as sm
    import statsmodels.formula.api as smf

    # initiates empty lists to hold the models, coefficients, standard errors, and 
    # fitted values
    model_list = []
    coefs = []
    stderr = []
    fit_vals = []

    # initializes a count at zero so it can be a reference for the ordered X column list
    count = 0
    # loops through the delta life expectancy columns
    for y in y_cols:
    
        # creates a dataframe where the X data is delta gdp per capita and y is life expectancy
        # at birth
        dat = pd.DataFrame()
        dat['X'] = df[X_cols[count]]
        dat['y'] = df[y]
    
        # regresses the change in y on the change in X with robust standard errors
        # in a given period and adds it to the list
        temp_model = smf.ols('y ~ X', data = dat).fit(cov_type = 'HC3')
        model_list.append(temp_model)
    
        # appends the coeffiecints, standard errors, and fitted values to their respective 
        # lists
        coefs.append(temp_model.params[1])
        stderr.append(temp_model.bse[1])
        fit_vals.append(temp_model.predict())
        
        # increments the column index
        count += 1
    
    # creates a dataframe and fills it with the lists collected earlier
    model = pd.DataFrame()
    model['Coef'] = coefs
    model['StdErr'] = stderr
    model['Fitted'] = fit_vals
    
    # returns the dataframe containing model info
    return(model, model_list)

# plots coefficients with error bars over time from the output from the repeated_reg()
# function
def coefs_over_time(model, start_year, end_year, step):
    
    # imports pyplot from the matplotlib library
    import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
    
    # plots the coeffients of gdp per capita growth for the model in each period
    # along with its standard error
    plt.errorbar(range(start_year, end_year + 1, step), model.Coef, yerr = model.StdErr)
    
    # generates and plots a red horizontal dotted line; if the error bar doesn't touch it, 
    # the coefficient is statistically significant at the alpha = 0.05 level
    horiz_line_data = np.array([0 for i in range(start_year + 1, end_year + 1, step)])
    plt.plot(range(start_year, end_year, step), horiz_line_data, 'r--')
    
    # adds a title
    plt.title('Coefficients With Error Bars Over Time')
    # displays the plot
    plt.show()
    
# creates a function to plot the residuals from fitted models, taking in the combined
# dataframe, the list of column names for the dependent variable, the model, and the
# year of the first observation from the non-differenced data

def display_resids(df, y_colnames, model, start_year, step):
    # this block of code displays the residuals from the differences in differences model
    # regressing life expectancy growth on gdp per capita growth

    # initializes the count at 1990 since it is the earliest observation prior to differencing
    count = start_year
    # initializes the count at 1990 since it is the earliest observation prior to differencing
    year = start_year
    # loops through the difference in differences model going period to next period
    for y in y_colnames:
        # creates a title
        title = 'Distribution of Residuals for ' + str(year)
        # plots the residuals (the actual value minus the predicted value)
        resids = df[y]- model.Fitted[count - start_year]
        plt.hist(resids)
        # adds a title
        plt.title(title)
        # adds a line at the mean
        plt.axvline(np.mean(resids), color = 'k', linestyle = 'dashed', linewidth = 1)
        # displays the plot
        plt.show()
        # increments the count so the model where the fitted values will change
        count += 1
        # increments the year so the years in the title will change
        year += step

A. Regressing Life Expectancy on ln(GDP per Capita)¶

As I expected, the returns to life expectancy from increases in GDP per capita are positive and appear decreasing over time. The mean of the residuals are approximately zero for all models in the sample period, although there is a slight left tail in the residuals for the models estimated in the later part of the sample period.

V. Conclusions¶

Looking at a scatter plot for the most recent data (2017) shows that there appears to be a very strong relationship between the two variables.

The coefficient for the most recent model regressing life expectancy on the natural log of GDP per capita is 4.6390 meaning a 1% increase in GDP per capita is associated with a 0.0462 year increase in life expectancy in 2017. The p-value for the coefficient is incredibly small in this model meaning the coefficient is statistically significant at any significance level.

My common sense hypothesis has been confirmed, like with the linkage between legalized marijuana and increased junk food sales (https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2019/02/190228134227.htm). But my analysis comes with a policy prescription. Although causation has not been established, the theory of healthy workers staying in the work force for longer and feeding additional tax revenue into the public health and public healthcare systems in a positive feedback cycle seems plausible, even with decreasing returns to life expectancy. The results of this exploration strongly suggest that investing in public health and public healthcare systems will have strong positive effects on the economy of a country, or likely any administrative unit.
